******
[2]
Date: Wed 28 Sep 2011
Source: KKTV [edited]
http://www.kktv.com/home/headlines/D70_Takes_Cantaloupe_Off_Menu_Due_To_Listeria_Scare_129834148.html


Dr Thomas Frieden, director of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, said Wednesday [28 Sep 2011] during a conference call with
media that 2 pregnant women were among the 72 confirmed cases of
_Listeria_ infection linked to cantaloupes grown in Colorado. He also
confirmed that this was the deadliest outbreak in more than a decade.

Both of the pregnant women and their fetuses are expected to be fine,
but 13 people have died from the infection. 3 more deaths are also
suspected to be connected, but are not yet confirmed by laboratory
tests.

The CDC says _Listeria_ infection during pregnancy could lead to
premature delivery, miscarriage, stillbirth, and other serious health
problems.

The CDC also said that the number of cases and deaths are likely to
increase, because symptoms of _Listeria_ infections can develop up to
2 months after consumption of the contaminated food.

The _Listeria_ infections were reported in 18 states.

In this case, laboratory tests have connected the strains of
_Listeria_ to melons of the "Rocky Ford" variety grown by Jensen Farms
in Holly, Colorado. That particular variety is prized for having a
higher sugar contact, and was developed in the Rocky Ford region of
Colorado during the late 1800's.

The state of Colorado says it has tested melon samples from the
refrigerator of a listeriosis patient's home, as well as samples
obtained from various retail outlets. They were also traced to Jensen
Farms.

Jensen Farms has voluntarily recalled the melons in question, which it
says were shipped between 29 Jul and 10 Sep 2011. They were sent to
Illinois, Wyoming, Tennessee, Utah, Texas, Colorado, Minnesota,
Kansas, New Mexico, North Carolina, Missouri, Nebraska, Oklahoma,
Arizona, New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania.

They carry stickers that say either, "Product of USA - Frontera
Produce - Colorado Fresh - Rocky Ford" or "Jensen Farms - Sweet Rocky
Fords."

Anyone who has, or may have had cantaloupes from Jensen Farms is
advised to throw them away. Do not try to clean the melons.

Additionally, the CDC warned that _Listeria_ can continue to grow --
even inside a refrigerator. Caution is advised for everyone who may
have had one of the recalled melons, but specifically for people who
are at high risk.

The FDA, also represented during Wednesday's [28 Sep 2011] conference
call, said this is the 1st known outbreak of listeriosis related to
cantaloupe. The 10 cantaloupe-related outbreaks in the past decade
were connected to salmonella or a virus.

The worst outbreak of listeriosis on record was in 1985 and traced
back to Mexican-style cheese.

The FDA says it has a team working with a team from Colorado to do an
environmental assessment at Jensen Farm's facilities. As part of that
work, they're looking at potential contamination from animals, water,
and the processing facility. So far, they've not reached any
conclusions.

A couple from Colorado Springs is suing the farm and Walmart because
of the tainted fruit. According to the lawsuit, obtained by 11 News,
they are alleging that a cantaloupe distributed by Jensen Farms and
sold at a Walmart on Razorback Road in the Springs caused [the man] to
fall ill with listeriosis. [He] has been hospitalized since 31 Aug
2011.

In the lawsuit, the couple claims that the cantaloupe was contaminated
with _Listeria_ at the time it was sold, and is directly responsible
for [his] illness. They say Jensen Farms and Walmart are both liable
for having sold "food which was defective and not reasonably safe."

If you have questions about listeriosis, call the Colorado Department
of Public Health and Environment at 1-877-462-2911.

Anyone with questions about the recall can contact Jensen Farms at
1-800-267-4561 or recall@rfordcantaloupe.com.

